'''The 2010 Guangxi Wildfire''' occurred in western [[Guangxi]], [[China]] during that year's spring season.
==Background== On Thursday, March 3, 2010, a [[wildfire]] ignited in the mountainous county of [[Longlin]] in Guangxi, China. [[Drought]] had already begun to impact the area previously, and the dry weather and lack of water contributed to the fire's success.<ref name="Relief Web 2">{{cite web|last1=Xinhua|last2=Xuequan|first2=Mu|title=More efforts needed to fight drought in SW China, says vice premier|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/china/more-efforts-needed-fight-drought-sw-china-says-vice-premier|website=Reliefweb.int|publisher=United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA)|accessdate=23 November 2015|ref=2}}</ref><ref name="Relief Web 3">{{cite web|last1=Oxfam|title=Oxfam provides water in China's worst drought in decades: 10 Million people short of drinking water|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/china/oxfam-provides-water-chinas-worst-drought-decades-10-million-people-short-drinking|website=Reliefweb.int|publisher=United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA)|accessdate=23 November 2015|ref=3}}</ref> The wildfire burned large volumes of forests and brush until it was finally put out six days and twenty-two hours later.<ref name="China Daily">{{cite web|last1=Xinhua|title=S China forest fire threatens nature reserve|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2010-03/04/content_9538253.htm|website=chinadaily.com|publisher=China Daily Information Co|accessdate=23 November 2015|ref=1}}</ref>
==Effects== According to Longlin County's fire control headquarters, a day after its ignition the fire had already burned 1,400 [[Chinese units of measurement|Mu]] (or about 93 [[hectares]] or 229 [[acres]]) of forestland, with a front spanning 5.3 kilometers. The fire was also heading towards the Zhongshan National Nature Reserve, where over two hundred of the endangered black-necked pheasant lived and were at risk of being affected by the traveling flames.<ref name="China Daily" />
Along with the area's locals, over one hundred firefighters and a [[Mi-26 helicopter]] were employed to suppress the fire.
After the fire was suppressed, the drought continued to worsen in the southern China region, especially in Guangxi.<ref name="Relief Web 4">{{cite web|last1=Xinhua|title=Severe drought expands in S China region|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/china/severe-drought-expands-s-china-region|website=Reliefweb.int|publisher=United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA)|accessdate=23 November 2015|ref=4}}</ref><ref name="Relief Web 5">{{cite web|last1=International Federation of Red Cross And Red Crescent Societies|title=China: Floods Information bulletin no 1|url=http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/51049192CB2B44828525774C004FE5A6-Full_Report.pdf|website=Reliefweb.int|publisher=United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs|accessdate=23 November 2015|ref=5}}</ref> Two months after the fire, torrential rain caused flash floods and landslides in the same area.<ref name="Relief Web 5" /><ref>NOAA National Centers for Environmental Information, State of the Climate: Global Hazards for June 2010, published online July 2010, retrieved on November 23, 2015 from http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/sotc/hazards/201006.</ref>
