{{Infobox television episode | title = Wieners Out | season = 20 | episode = 4 | airdate = {{Start date|2016|10|12}} | director = [[Trey Parker]] | writer = Trey Parker | production = 2004 | season_article = South Park (season 20) | episode_list = List of South Park episodes | prev = [[The Damned (South Park)|The Damned]] | next = [[Douche and a Danish]] }} "'''Wieners Out'''" is the fourth episode in the [[South Park (season 20)|twentieth season]] of the American animated television series ''[[South Park]]''. The 271st episode of the series overall, it first aired on [[Comedy Central]] in the United States on October 12, 2016.
The episode lampooned modern social protest movements and campaigns (like [[Free the Nipple (campaign)|Free the Nipple]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sniderson|first1=Dan|title=Comic-Con 2016: South Park creators talk Pokemon, killing Kenny again|url=http://ew.com/article/2016/07/23/comic-con-south-park-panel-pokemon-kill-kenny/|accessdate=21 May 2017|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=23 July 2016}}</ref> and [[Black Lives Matter]]) and commented on [[Anonymous post|Internet anonymity]], while also progressing the plot and themes of the season's previous episodes.
==Plot== A Danish narrator explains the Danish history of dealing with [[troll]]s and that now they are on a quest to take out the newest variety, the [[Internet troll]]. [[Gerald and Sheila Broflovski|Gerald Broflovski]] feels the pressure of being found out for his trolling as Skankhunt42, and he tries as much as he can to cover it up. Meanwhile, [[Kyle Broflovski|Kyle]] feels guilt over the rift between the boys and the girls. When he tries to bring them together, it only strains their relationships further, and [[Butters Stotch|Butters]] takes on a leadership role after the elementary school girls convince his long-distance girlfriend Charlotte to dump him online. He takes down his pants, exposing his [[penis]], in protest of feeling neutered, at a girls' volleyball game. Most of the boys immediately follow suit, disgusting the girls even more. Gerald struggles with his trolling withdrawal, eventually meeting with a fellow troll known as Dildo Schwaggins under a bridge, who warns Gerald of an upcoming attack from the [[Danes]]. Gerald eventually succumbs to the pressure and Sheila catches him in the bathroom while trolling on an iPad that Sheila bought for him. Still reluctant to reveal his inner troll self, Gerald lies to Sheila, saying that he was watching "[[urolagnia|piss porn]]", and he agrees to be urinated on to cover up his secret. He even attends an addiction meeting, but it turns out to be for [[Member Berries|member berry]] addicts instead.
When talking with [[Eric Cartman|Cartman]] and [[List of students at South Park Elementary#Heidi Turner|Heidi Turner]], who are now boyfriend and girlfriend, Kyle realizes that he will not be able to stop Butters, who is now leading protest marches without pants, from worsening the rift on his own, so he attempts to get Cartman on his side. Cartman refuses since he feels that he is happier with Heidi, away from the divisiveness of groups and social media. Schwaggins shows Gerald a video by the [[BBC News]] that explains a Danish website known as Troll Trace designed to track down the real-life identity of Internet trolls is coming online. The founder of the site threatens to expose trolls everywhere, although he is aware that his methods will have the greater effect of stripping anonymity from anyone posting on the Internet. Schwaggins and Gerald retreat to a group of other trolls. Kyle meets up with the boys and girls at the school cafeteria, where he announces that he now agrees to Butters' protest. As he pulls out his penis in front of them, most of the girls leave in disgust, and the boys cheer and carry him out on their shoulders.
==Reception== Jesse Schedeen from [[IGN]] rated the episode a 8.4 out of 10, and commented that he loved the "more focused episode this week as the series continues to lampoon social media."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schedeen|first1=Jesse|title=South Park: "Wieners Out" Review|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/10/13/south-park-wieners-out-review|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=October 13, 2016|date=October 12, 2016}}</ref> Jeremy Lambert with 411 Mania gave it a 7.5 out of 10, summarizing his review with the comment "There's no denying the brilliance of South Park when they are focused on a story."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lambert|first1=Jeremy|title=South Park 20.4 Review – "Wieners Out"|url=http://411mania.com/movies/south-park-20-4-review-wieners-out/|website=411 Mania|accessdate=October 13, 2016|date=October 13, 2016}}</ref> Dan Caffrey from ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' rated the episode an A- and found the scene with Sheila urinating on Gerald while Ike and Kyle watch from the doorway "the kind of nasty sight gag that's become a staple of the ''South Park'' universe."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caffrey|first1=Dan|title="Wieners Out" • South Park • TV Review After a week off, South Park returns with a memorable gross-out gag|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/south-park-keeps-its-endgame-flux-and-its-sight-ga-244136|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=October 13, 2016|date=October 13, 2016}}</ref> Chris Longo with ''[[Den of Geek]]'' rated it 3.5 out of 5 stars, still continuing his theory that this season "is still Eric Cartman's ''South Park'', one we've been building up to for decades."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Longo|first1=Chris|title=South Park: Weiners Out Review|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/south-park/259207/south-park-weiners-out-review|website=[[Den of Geek]]|accessdate=October 13, 2016|date=October 13, 2016}}</ref>
